**1. `parseDependencies.ts` — return `{ number, kind }[]`**

Return type changes from `number[]` to `{ number: number; kind: 'hard' | 'soft' }[]`.

Internally, use a `Map<number, 'hard' | 'soft'>` so hard overrides soft if the same `#N` appears both ways:

```ts
const deps = new Map<number, 'hard' | 'soft'>();
const record = (n: number, kind: 'hard' | 'soft') => {
  const existing = deps.get(n);
  if (existing === 'hard') return; // hard wins, never downgrade
  deps.set(n, kind);
};

// Hard triggers
for (const m of body.matchAll(/(?:depends on|blocked by|requires|after)\s+#(\d+)/gi)) {
  record(parseInt(m[1], 10), 'hard');
}
// Soft inline triggers
for (const m of body.matchAll(/(?:related to|see also)\s+#(\d+)/gi)) {
  record(parseInt(m[1], 10), 'soft');
}
// Soft section scan
const sectionPattern = /(?:^|\n)#{1,4}\s*[^\n]*related[^\n]*\n([\s\S]*?)(?=\n#{1,6}\s|$)/gi;
for (const sm of body.matchAll(sectionPattern)) {
  for (const rm of sm[1].matchAll(/#(\d+)/g)) {
    record(parseInt(rm[1], 10), 'soft');
  }
}

return [...deps.entries()]
  .filter(([n]) => releaseIssueNumbers.has(n))
  .map(([number, kind]) => ({ number, kind }));
```

Update the docstring to remove the line saying there's no edge-type distinction.

**2. `useDependencyGraph.ts` — set strokeDasharray on soft edges**

The edge-builder loop currently iterates `deps.forEach((depNumber) => ...)`. After the parser change `deps` is `{ number, kind }[]`, so rename:

```ts
deps.forEach((dep) => {
  const sourceStatus = statusByNodeId.get(String(dep.number));
  const targetStatus = statusByNodeId.get(String(issue.number));
  const isFlowing =
    (sourceStatus === 'completed' || sourceStatus === 'closed') &&
    targetStatus === 'executing';

  edges.push({
    id: `e${dep.number}-${issue.number}`,
    source: String(dep.number),
    target: String(issue.number),
    animated: isFlowing,
    data: { kind: dep.kind },
    style: dep.kind === 'soft' ? { strokeDasharray: '6 4' } : undefined,
    markerEnd: { type: MarkerType.ArrowClosed, width: 16, height: 16 },
  });
});
```

Note: `dep.number` (not `depNumber`) — the variable name changes. Also note `data: { kind }` for downstream consumers (helpful for future analytics, optional but cheap).

**3. `DependencyGraph.tsx` — preserve dashed style through overlays**

The two `styledEdges` overlays currently write `style: { stroke, strokeWidth, opacity }` which fully replaces the base style. If we want soft edges to STAY dashed in Critical Path / hover-lineage modes, spread the base in:

```ts
// Lineage block (line ~134):
style: {
  ...edge.style,
  stroke: 'var(--text-secondary, #555)',
  strokeWidth: inLineage ? 2.5 : 2,
  opacity: inLineage ? 1 : 0.15,
},

// Critical-path block (line ~148):
style: {
  ...edge.style,
  stroke: isOnPath ? '#f59e0b' : 'var(--text-secondary, #555)',
  strokeWidth: isOnPath ? 3 : 2,
  opacity: isOnPath ? 1 : 0.3,
},
```

The spread preserves `strokeDasharray` while overlay-specific keys (stroke, strokeWidth, opacity) still win.

**4. `DependencyGraph.tsx` — legend update**

After the status dot entries (around line 287, before the optional critical-path entry), add solid + dashed edge legend entries:

```tsx
<span className="dependency-graph-legend-item">
  <span className="dependency-graph-legend-edge dependency-graph-legend-edge-solid" /> Depends on
</span>
<span className="dependency-graph-legend-item">
  <span className="dependency-graph-legend-edge dependency-graph-legend-edge-dashed" /> Related to
</span>
```

**5. `DependencyGraph.css` — legend edge swatch styling**

Add small visual swatches for the legend (12x2px line segments, solid and dashed):
```css
.dependency-graph-legend-edge {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 14px;
  height: 0;
  border-top: 2px solid var(--text-secondary, #888);
  margin-right: 6px;
  vertical-align: middle;
}
.dependency-graph-legend-edge-dashed {
  border-top-style: dashed;
}
```

The dashed border-style on a 14px-wide element renders as a couple of dashes — visually consistent with the edge style on the graph.

**Edge cases:**
- An issue mentions #42 under '## Related' AND elsewhere says 'depends on #42' → hard wins (the record() helper enforces this).
- Soft section heading like '## Related Research' (instead of '## Related') → still matched (regex is `[^\n]*related[^\n]*`).
- Critical path on a soft edge → solid amber overlay, but dashed pattern preserved by the style spread. Some visual tension (amber + dashed), but truthful: the critical chain goes through a soft reference.
- Animation from #151 on a dashed edge → ReactFlow's animation moves the dash pattern itself, which looks especially good (literal flowing dashes).
